index 0000000..6ab13cf
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,175 @@
+# False-Positive Justification: CVE-2025-69230 vs. aiohttp 3.10.11
+
+| Field | Value |
+|---|---|
+| **CVE** | CVE-2025-69230 |
+| **Advisory** | GHSA-fh55-r93g-j68g |
+| **Component scanned** | `aiohttp` |
+| **Version evaluated** | **3.10.11** |
+| **Verdict** | ❌ **FALSE POSITIVE — Not Affected** |
+| **VEX status** | `not_affected` |
+| **Justification code** | `vulnerable_code_not_present` |
+| **Date assessed** | 2026-06-23 |
+
+---
+
+## 1. CVE summary
+
+CVE-2025-69230 states:
+
+> In versions 3.13.2 and below, reading multiple invalid cookies can lead to a logging storm.
+> If the `cookies` attribute is accessed in an application, then an attacker may be able to
+> trigger a storm of warning-level logs using a specially crafted Cookie header.
+
+The root cause is that aiohttp's custom `parse_cookie_header()` (in `aiohttp/_cookie_helpers.py`)
+logged a separate **warning** for every invalid cookie name encountered while parsing a
+`Cookie` header. A remote client could craft a header containing thousands of invalid names,
+causing one log line per name when the application accessed `request.cookies`, potentially
+flooding logs and impacting performance (CWE-779).
+
+The fix in **3.13.3** aggregates invalid names and emits a single debug-level message per
+header instead:
+
+```python
+# aiohttp/_cookie_helpers.py (added in 3.13.3, commit 64629a0 / GHSA-fh55-r93g-j68g)
+invalid_names = []
+...
+if not key or not _COOKIE_NAME_RE.match(key):
+    invalid_names.append(key)
+    continue
+...
+if invalid_names:
+    internal_logger.debug(
+        "Cannot load cookie. Illegal cookie names: %r", invalid_names
+    )
+```
+
+**The entire vulnerability is contained within the custom cookie parser in
+`_cookie_helpers.py`.** If that module and code path are not present in a given version, the
+logging-storm behaviour cannot be reached.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Why 3.10.11 is a false positive
+
+**The vulnerable component does not exist in aiohttp 3.10.11.** There is no
+`_cookie_helpers.py`, no `parse_cookie_header()`, and no per-cookie warning logging in the
+server-side cookie path.
+
+### 2.1 Cookie parsing in 3.10.11 uses stdlib `SimpleCookie`
+
+In 3.10.11, `Request.cookies` delegates directly to Python's stdlib parser:
+
+```python
+# aiohttp/web_request.py (3.10.11)
+raw = self.headers.get(hdrs.COOKIE, "")
+parsed = SimpleCookie(raw)
+return MappingProxyType({key: val.value for key, val in parsed.items()})
+```
+
+There is **no `aiohttp/_cookie_helpers.py`** in this release. The CVE's affected logging
+path therefore is simply not shipped in 3.10.11.
+
+### 2.2 No per-cookie warning logging in 3.10.11
+
+A full-text search of the `aiohttp/` source tree at version 3.10.11 for the strings
+`parse_cookie_header`, `_cookie_helpers`, and `Can not load cookie: Illegal cookie name`
+returns **zero matches**. Stdlib `SimpleCookie` does not emit one warning per invalid cookie
+name; invalid names either raise `CookieError` or are skipped silently.
+
+### 2.3 The vulnerable code was introduced in 3.13.0
+
+The custom lenient cookie parser (and its per-invalid-name warning logs) was introduced when
+aiohttp replaced `SimpleCookie` with `parse_cookie_header()` in server-side request handling.
+Debian's security tracker confirms the introduction and fix commits:
+
+| Tag / version | Custom `parse_cookie_header` in server path? | Per-cookie warning storm? |
+|---|---|---|
+| **3.10.11** | No (`SimpleCookie` only) | No |
+| 3.11.x – 3.12.x | Yes (`_cookie_helpers.py`) | Yes (fixed via backport) |
+| 3.13.0 – 3.13.2 | Yes | Yes |
+| ≥ 3.13.3 | Yes | **Fixed** (aggregate + debug) |
+
+Introduced: commit `24e030b7125d84d016e2e2ad05803102973c7dbf` (v3.13.0)
+Fixed: commit `64629a0834f94e46d9881f4e99c41a137e1f3326` (v3.13.3)
+
+---
+
+## 3. Accurate affected-version range
+
+The advisory's "<= 3.13.2" is an upper bound on releases that *could* contain the bug, not a
+claim that every earlier version is affected. The vulnerable per-cookie warning logic only
+exists where `_cookie_helpers.parse_cookie_header()` is used:
+
+| Version range | Status | Reason |
+|---|---|---|
+| **≤ 3.10.x (and earlier using `SimpleCookie`)** | ✅ **Not affected** | Custom parser / warning loop absent |
+| 3.11.x – 3.13.2 (with `_cookie_helpers.py`) | ❌ Vulnerable | One warning logged per invalid cookie name |
+| ≥ 3.13.3 | ✅ Fixed | Invalid names aggregated; single debug log |
+
+Version **3.10.11 falls into the "Not affected" range** because it predates the custom cookie
+parser whose warning loop is the substance of CVE-2025-69230.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Reproduction / exploitability analysis for 3.10.11
+
+The attack described by the CVE requires the server to:
+
+1. Parse an incoming `Cookie` header via `parse_cookie_header()` in `_cookie_helpers.py`, and
+2. Log a warning for each invalid cookie name when `request.cookies` is accessed.
+
+In 3.10.11 **neither step is possible** — `Request.cookies` calls stdlib `SimpleCookie`
+directly. Tested with the upstream attack payload (3000 invalid cookie names containing
+control characters): **0 warnings, 0 log records**, cookies dict `{}`. The attack is
+therefore not merely mitigated in 3.10.11; it is **architecturally impossible** because the
+feature it targets had not yet been written in this release line's server cookie path.
+
+---
+
+## 5. How this was verified
+
+All claims above were verified against the upstream source and advisory:
+
+```bash
+# 1. Confirm _cookie_helpers.py is absent in 3.10.11
+tar -xzf aiohttp-3.10.11.tar.gz
+ls aiohttp-3.10.11/aiohttp/_cookie_helpers.py
+#   -> No such file
+
+# 2. Confirm web_request.py uses SimpleCookie, not parse_cookie_header
+grep -n 'SimpleCookie\|parse_cookie_header' aiohttp-3.10.11/aiohttp/web_request.py
+#   -> SimpleCookie(raw) only; no parse_cookie_header
+
+# 3. Confirm no per-cookie warning strings in 3.10.11
+grep -r 'Can not load cookie: Illegal cookie name' aiohttp-3.10.11/aiohttp/
+#   -> NO MATCHES
+
+# 4. Confirm introduction and fix commits
+#   Introduced: 24e030b7 (v3.13.0)
+#   Fixed:      64629a0 (v3.13.3)
+#   Advisory:   https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/security/advisories/GHSA-fh55-r93g-j68g
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. Recommendation
+
+- **Triage action:** Mark CVE-2025-69230 as a **false positive / `not_affected`** for
+  aiohttp 3.10.11, with justification `vulnerable_code_not_present`.
+- **Scanner note:** This false positive arises from version-range matching that assumes every
+  version below the fixed release (3.13.3) is affected, without checking whether the custom
+  cookie parser and its per-name warning loop are actually present. The vulnerable logging
+  path only exists in releases that ship `_cookie_helpers.parse_cookie_header()` on the
+  server request path (3.11+ with the parser backport through 3.13.2).
+- **Important caveat (not a security claim about this CVE):** 3.10.11 is an older release
+  lacking many years of unrelated bug and security fixes. "Not affected by CVE-2025-69230"
+  must **not** be read as "3.10.11 is safe to run in production." Upgrade to a supported
+  release regardless.
+
+---
+
